                        <!--  *************************************  <handDesc>  ********************************* -->

                        <handDesc hands="1">
                            <handNote ana="#inscribed"> While the orthography of the text is
                                generally characteristic of early imperial style, some aspects of
                                note include the simple one stroke interpuncts seemingly only used
                                after Tiberius, Cissonius, and <hi rend="italic">vixit</hi>, with no standardization across
                                the three and the one following Tiberius being most prominent. The
                                letters are standardized with the exception of the T in <hi rend="italic">merenti</hi>
                                being slanted towards the left in a fashion which diverges from the
                                other instances of the letter. </handNote>
                        </handDesc>

                        <!--  *************************************  <decoDesc>  *********************************     -->
                        <decoDesc>
                            <decoNote>
                                <p>The campus follows the general rectangular shape and is set off
                                    by a patterned frame consisting of evenly spaced dash
                                    indentations at the top and bottom and triangles with serpentine
                                    patterning forming tabula ansata at the corners of the campus.
                                    Two holes have been drilled into the marble flanking the campus
                                    equidistant from one another, so the plaque could be hung
                                    underneath or above a <hi rend="italic">columbarium</hi> burial. </p>
                            </decoNote>
                        </decoDesc>
