    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="edition">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName><name type="praenomen" key="Tiberius"><expan><abbr>Ti</abbr><ex>berius</ex></expan></name> <name type="gentilicium" key="Claudius">Claudius</name> 
                    <lb n="2"/><name type="cognomen" key="Cissonius">Cissonius</name></persName> <expan><abbr>v</abbr><ex>ixit</ex></expan> <expan><abbr>a</abbr><ex>nnis</ex></expan> <num type="cardinal" value="20">XX</num>. 
                    <lb n="3"/><persName><name type="cognomen" key="Thallusa">Thallusa</name></persName> <supplied reason="subaudible">fecit</supplied> coniugi 
                    <lb n="4"/>bene merenti. 
                </ab>
            </div>
            
            <div type="translation">
            <p>"Tiberius Claudius Cissonius lived 20 years. Thallusa [made this] for her well-deserving
                    husband."</p></div>

            <div type="commentary">
            <p>The text records epitaph for Ti. Claudius Cissonius made by his wife Thallusa. While
                    the specific name of Ti. Claudius Cissonius does not seem to be extant
                    elsewhere, the name would imply the piece can be dated no earlier than the reign
                    of Tiberius Claudius. Additionally, the piece can be dated no later than ca.
                    120, because <hi rend="italic">columbaria</hi> burials ceased to be used after that period. </p></div>
            

